      "writtenOn": "2016-03-03T19:18:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "More of a design question - why do you need a common base class for recorder and player? Also, why does the player need to \"follow\" any widgets?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 25,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 25,
        "endChar": 25
      },
      "revId": "f23da3defbef82cb4436b1d6e7d18a877712a034",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "82ea9d1e_8723368f",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-record-player.h",
        "patchSetId": 11
      },
      "lineNbr": 25,
      "author": {
        "id": 1058003
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-03-03T19:51:26Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The player \"follows\" widgets to make it unnecessary to search for them.  The shared followed list and common start/stop interface (that would make these additions similar to how ui-event-recorder is used in emulator-qt-window currently) is how the design came to be. \n\nI understand that identifying a widget by its full name in the qt tree is possible, but then again I preferred not to do this. Mostly because I think it is unnecessary for the use-cases of this item at the time, but also because I thought this way event records would be more likely to be replay-able in the future. The likelihood of changing a unique followed widget name, thus rendering previously saved event-records un-replayable, is smaller than the likelihood of any dynamic naming scheme covering all layouts and widgets that might be changed/introduced in the future. So I thought about it and preferred the \"follow\" function, to render users of the record/replay utility responsible for keeping it working.",
      "parentUuid": "c26bb568_290d9089",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 25,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 25,
        "endChar": 25
      },
